# 🧠 Entra Phishing-Resistant Authentication Design

This document defines the architecture, controls, and configuration for implementing phishing-resistant authentication in Microsoft Entra ID.

---

# 🎯 Objectives

- Eliminate password-based authentication where possible  
- Enforce phishing-resistant authentication  
- Protect privileged accounts with highest assurance  
- Provide scalable authentication for standard users  
- Maintain secure recovery paths  

---

# 🏗️ High-Level Architecture

```mermaid
flowchart TD
    A[User Sign-In] --> B{User Type}

    B -->|Privileged| C[YubiKey Required]
    B -->|Standard| D[Passkey Required]

    C --> E[Phishing-Resistant Authentication]
    D --> F[Authenticator / Windows Hello]

    E --> G[Conditional Access Evaluation]
    F --> G

    G --> H{Policy Decision}

    H -->|Compliant| I[Access Granted]
    H -->|Non-Compliant| J[Blocked]

    I --> K[Application Access]

    J --> L[Remediation / TAP]

    M[Break-Glass Account] --> I

🔐 Authentication Model
- Privileged Users
- YubiKey (FIDO2 security key)
- Hardware-backed authentication
- No fallback to weaker methods
- Standard Users
- Microsoft Authenticator passkeys (required)
- Windows Hello for Business (optional)
- Passwordless authentication
- Recovery Methods
- Temporary Access Pass (TAP)
- Break-glass account (excluded from policies)

🛡️ Conditional Access Design
- Policy Segmentation
- Policy	Target	Enforcement
- Privileged Policy	Admin roles	Phishing-resistant MFA (YubiKey)
- Passkey Policy	Standard users	Phishing-resistant MFA
- Lab Policy	Pilot users	MFA (report-only)
- Core Controls
- Assignments

Users:
- Include: Target group
- Exclude: Break-glass account

Applications:
- All cloud apps

Client apps:
- Browser
- Mobile and desktop clients
- Grant Controls
- Lab Policy
- Require MFA

Production Policy
- Require authentication strength:
- Phishing-resistant MFA
- Session Controls
- Not configured for privileged accounts
- Optional for standard users

⚠️ Policy Interaction Considerations

Ensure policies do not conflict:

- Privileged (YubiKey) policy
- Passkey policy
- Legacy MFA policies

Conflicts may cause:

- Authentication loops
- Incorrect MFA prompts
- Access failures

🛡️ Defender for Cloud Apps Integration
- Recommended Use
- Standard users only
- Data protection scenarios
- Avoid For
- Privileged accounts
- Admin portals
- Risks
- Session disruption
- Authentication flow issues

🧾 Licensing Requirements
Capability	Requirement
Conditional Access	Entra ID P1
Authentication Strengths	Entra ID P1
Risk-based policies	Entra ID P2 (optional)

🧪 Validation Strategy
- Lab Phase
- Report-only policies
- Pilot group testing
- Authentication verification

Production Phase
- Enforce authentication strength
- Block password-based sign-in
- Monitor sign-in logs

Success Criteria
- Passkey authentication works consistently
- Password sign-in blocked
- No unexpected MFA prompts
- Break-glass access verified

🛠️ Operational Model
- User Lifecycle
- Event	Action
- New user	Register passkey
- Lost device	Issue TAP
- Device replacement	Re-register passkey
- Monitoring
- Sign-in logs
- Conditional Access insights
- Authentication method usage

🔐 Security Controls Summary
- Control	Purpose
- FIDO2 / Passkeys	Phishing-resistant auth
- Conditional Access	Enforcement
- Authentication Strengths	Method restriction
- TAP	Recovery
- Break-glass	Emergency access

🧠 Design Principles
- Zero Trust architecture
- Least privilege access
- Phishing-resistant enforcement
- Separation of user risk levels
- Recovery-first design

📌 Final Architecture Summary
Privileged Users:
  → YubiKey (required)

Standard Users:
  → Authenticator passkeys (required)
  → Windows Hello (optional)

Fallback:
  → Temporary Access Pass (TAP)
  → Break-glass account

This design delivers strong, scalable, and secure authentication aligned with modern Zero Trust principles.

